# General Project Rules

## Tech Stack
Lesury is a **Turbo monorepo** with npm workspaces. The core stack is **Next.js 16 (App Router)**, **TypeScript**, **Tailwind CSS v4**, **ShadCN UI **, **PartyKit** (real-time server), **Framer Motion**, and **partysocket**.

### Monorepo Structure
- `apps/web` — Next.js web app (TV host screens + phone player screens)
- `apps/server` — PartyKit real-time server for game state sync via WebSockets
- `packages/game-logic` — Shared pure game logic (used by both web and server)
- `packages/config` — Shared ESLint and TypeScript configs

## Reuse Existing Components — CRITICAL
- **Before creating any new component, always check if an equivalent already exists.** Search `components/` and `app/components/` first.
- **Never recreate or duplicate functionality** that is already provided by an existing component, ShadCN UI primitive, or game-logic function.
- Only create new files when the needed functionality genuinely does not exist in the codebase.
- If a ShadCN component is not yet installed, add it via `npx shadcn@latest add <component>` in `apps/web`.


## Icons
- **Use Lucide icons** (`lucide-react`) — this is the ShadCN default icon library configured in `components.json`.
- For game-specific custom icons, inline SVG components are acceptable.

## Typography & Fonts
- **Use the Source Code Pro font** (loaded via `next/font/google` in `app/layout.tsx`, exposed as `--font-source-code-pro`).
- All three font families (`--font-sans`, `--font-mono`, `--font-serif`) are mapped to Source Code Pro in the Tailwind theme.
- Apply font weights intentionally: `font-normal` (400) for body, `font-medium` (500) for labels, `font-semibold` (600) / `font-bold` (700) for headings.

## Styling
- **Use Tailwind CSS v4 utility classes.** No `tailwind.config.js` — configuration lives in `globals.css` via `@theme inline`.
- Never write custom CSS files or inline `style={{}}` props unless absolutely unavoidable.
- Use the project's design tokens (CSS variables) for colors — never hardcode hex values.
- Follow a mobile-first approach: default styles for mobile, `md:` and `lg:` for larger screens.
- Use **Framer Motion** for animations (`framer-motion`).

## TypeScript
- **Always use TypeScript.** Never use `.js` or `.jsx` files.
- Avoid `any`. Use proper types or `unknown` with type narrowing.
- Game types are defined within `packages/game-logic/src/games/<game>/types.ts`.

## File & Folder Structure
- Pages and layouts go in `apps/web/app/` (App Router conventions).
- Reusable components go in `apps/web/components/`.
- Utility functions go in `apps/web/lib/`.
- Game logic lives in `packages/game-logic/src/games/<game-name>/`.

## Game Architecture Pattern
Each game follows this structure:
- **Landing page:** `app/games/<game>/page.tsx` — game description and start/join UI.
- **Host page:** `app/games/<game>/host/page.tsx` — TV screen view (renders `<Game>Host` component).
- **Player page:** `app/games/<game>/player/page.tsx` — phone controller view (renders `<Game>Player` component).
- **Host component:** `components/games/<game>/<Game>Host.tsx` — game board/display logic.
- **Player component:** `components/games/<game>/<Game>Player.tsx` — player controls/input logic.
- **Game logic:** `packages/game-logic/src/games/<game>/` — pure state machine, reducer, types.
- **Server handler:** `apps/server/src/server.ts` — PartyKit WebSocket message routing.

When adding a new game, follow this exact pattern. Reuse `GameLayout`, `RoomHost`, and `RoomPlayer` components.

## Real-Time Communication
- The server uses **PartyKit** for WebSocket-based real-time game state.
- The web app connects via **partysocket** (`PartySocket`).
- Game state is managed server-side; clients send actions and receive state updates.
